<subSubSection id="0CC01698B51485EB3A582E232E03DA05" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3F565706A127A387EE43A064A125E16D" pageNumber="10">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D30721261F783B4C76EACB8CFA630AD8" pageNumber="10">
The types of many nominal glyptosternine species are deposited in Indian and Chinese institutions, and are usually fairly inaccessible to researchers. This produces obstacles to easy comparison when new species of glyptosternines are described. The problem is also exacerbated by the limited availability of non-type material for comparison in institutions outside of China and India. Glyptosternine catfishes live in habitats that are difficult for researchers to gain access to and are difficult to capture using conventional sampling methods; these are the primary reasons for the paucity of (non-type) comparative material. Furthermore, much of this comparative material actually consists of material exchanged from Indian or Chinese institutions (for example, all the paratypes of 
<taxonomicName id="EEBEF20D952C34488AF742D9EA58384A" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7B7369B8-E382-4718-827C-4931C8F60FBB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis macropterus Ng 2004:3" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macropterus">P. macropterus</taxonomicName>
had been exchanged from the Kunming Institute of Zoology in Yunnan, China). However, these obstacles can be overcome and adequate comparisons are possible, at least for the species described within the last 50 years, by using the data from the original descriptions. It is with this limitation in mind that the two species described herein are compared with other congeners.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13707BBEFDEFEA37931DDC63940DFDBA" lastPageNumber="11" pageNumber="10">
<taxonomicName id="59F568FF96312F1F85C36410A02821F3" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7B7369B8-E382-4718-827C-4931C8F60FBB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis macropterus Ng 2004:3" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macropterus">Pareuchiloglanis macropterus</taxonomicName>
has often been misidentified as 
<taxonomicName id="14C001B1C37D31B53F0F3B92AEB958B9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamengensis">P. kamengensis</taxonomicName>
in the literature, but can be distinguished from it by the characters stated in the diagnosis. Furthermore, the two species are found in different drainages (
<taxonomicName id="9684D8B30BFD01823659306618A90F31" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7B7369B8-E382-4718-827C-4931C8F60FBB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis macropterus Ng 2004:3" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macropterus">P. macropterus</taxonomicName>
from the Salween River and Irrawaddy River drainages and 
<taxonomicName id="1EAFEC3D2E1DA9CEB1FE10D731D3638D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamengensis">P. kamengensis</taxonomicName>
from the Brahmaputra River drainage) and are not likely to be conspecific, as glyptosternine catfishes, like many other highly specialized rheophilic fish species, have very restricted distributions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2CD8E1C9A9521C4FDA9DC9057CBEA100" pageNumber="11">
Additional characters may exist to distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="BC08467E4907649B4EB010F380F9D8EC" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7B7369B8-E382-4718-827C-4931C8F60FBB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis macropterus Ng 2004:3" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macropterus">P. macropterus</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="26E6FD1982ADDD5D178DF492351F7261" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamengensis">P. kamengensis</taxonomicName>
. The specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF4263B7EE605420CFBEDB2D7EC8D7" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamengensis">P. kamengensis</taxonomicName>
collected from the Yarlong Tsangpo River (a tributary of the Brahmaputra River upstream of the type locality of 
<taxonomicName id="17C8F123AE08AA0C931C10E0005C332D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamengensis">P. kamengensis</taxonomicName>
) illustrated in Wu &amp; Wu (1992: Fig. 155) shows a distinct postlabial and thoracic groove not present in 
<taxonomicName id="475EEE9CCB466A65B3522DEE90EC0BF1" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7B7369B8-E382-4718-827C-4931C8F60FBB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis macropterus Ng 2004:3" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macropterus">P. macropterus</taxonomicName>
, as well as the disposition of the premaxillary teeth in two distinct patches (although the accompanying text mentions the teeth as being arranged in a single band). The validities of these characters await confirmation by direct comparison of specimens and are therefore not used as diagnostic for the species. The figure does illustrate, however, some of the characters that distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="9C63E886EB9FBAD9271AC5A531DB93E4" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamengensis">P. kamengensis</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="0B8DCD92DD81F382BFD9C523D088C7CD" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7B7369B8-E382-4718-827C-4931C8F60FBB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis macropterus Ng 2004:3" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macropterus">P. macropterus</taxonomicName>
(such as the shorter adipose fin).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D506A96ED7AF17F02D0FF82799DE8283" pageNumber="11">
Although the pale-colored patches on the body of 
<taxonomicName id="22CECD51795654B43710833EC9D28445" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7B7369B8-E382-4718-827C-4931C8F60FBB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis macropterus Ng 2004:3" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macropterus">P. macropterus</taxonomicName>
are not particularly evident in Fig. 1, they can still be made out with some difficulty in pale specimens (as in Fig. 1), and are clearly visible in darker specimens (the BMNH paratypes). The presence of these patches is also mentioned in the literature and amply illustrated (e.g. Chu et al., 1990).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="58116E07253846BC63257FF396843852" pageNumber="11">
There are only two species of 
<taxonomicName id="12532082C901056D22134401680651C6" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1C6AC061-0134-487B-9102-EFF719A47063" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis Pellegrin 1936:245" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pareuchiloglanis</taxonomicName>
reported from the Red River (Song Hong) drainage: 
<taxonomicName id="1D8FDDF061C0287EEA041C8DCDC898BA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrotrema">P. macrotrema</taxonomicName>
(known from the Red River (Song Hong) drainage in Lao Cai province) and 
<taxonomicName id="DC2D7856CE84429DDCD2865DE2A180A8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:83B65CFA-1F1E-4A82-A9E6-0E2F4BEDF726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis rhabdurus Ng 2004:7" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rhabdurus">P. rhabdurus</taxonomicName>
(found further to the west in the Song Lo drainage). The only other species reported from the region is 
<taxonomicName id="E3E1A8ABC21789D7DBB82C1F10876114" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:AF241874-BEBF-4718-B795-BF5807DD0826" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis nebulifer Ng &amp; Kottelat 2000:11" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nebulifer">P. nebulifer</taxonomicName>
, which is known only from the Song Ma drainage, which lies immediately adjacent southwards to the Red River (Song Hong) drainage. Given how poorly the freshwater ichthyofauna of northern Vietnam is currently understood (Kottelat, 2001), it would not be surprising that more 
<taxonomicName id="D0721F7DE4EAA6C0296B33A564E06979" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1C6AC061-0134-487B-9102-EFF719A47063" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis Pellegrin 1936:245" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pareuchiloglanis</taxonomicName>
species await discovery there.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D5A41137815E362FB8FA330E681A97B" pageNumber="11">
The material identified as 
<taxonomicName id="975A76170A8932F19C96E7BE9E45C658" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrotrema">P. macrotrema</taxonomicName>
by Chu et al. (1990) from the upper Red River (Yuanjiang) drainage in China probably represents an undescribed species. As noted in Kottelat (2001), differences exist between the Vietnamese and Chinese material, with the former having a shorter caudal peduncle (13.7-18.2% SL vs. 20.8-24.4). However, the Chinese material was unavailable to me for further verification of its status. Another undescribed 
<taxonomicName id="F6E139C7115ECB41FEFFC555435836A3" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1C6AC061-0134-487B-9102-EFF719A47063" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pareuchiloglanis Pellegrin 1936:245" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pareuchiloglanis</taxonomicName>
species from the Salween River (Nujiang) drainage possibly exists. The material identified as 
<taxonomicName id="F4654EA4744548FEE2FF3A57BC161D3E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="feae">P. feae</taxonomicName>
by Chu et al. (1990) is characterized by distinctly separate (vs. confluent) adipose and caudal fins and therefore does not appear to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="C797C2A55F2497B0EF851EDEE4981CA1" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pareuchiloglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="feae">P. feae</taxonomicName>
s. str.. Again, I was unable to obtain material to verify its identity.
</paragraph>
